post_text:
The Barons are celebrating one of their own - Sacha Standish, a 16 year teacher in the Buckeye Valley District, has been selected for the Fulbright Teachers for Global Classrooms, a program sponsored by the U.S. Department of State and the J. William Fulbright Foreign Scholarship Board. A Fifth through Eighth Grade Language Arts and Social Studies Teacher, Ms. Standish is one of 71 U.S. citizens who will travel abroad through the Fulbright Teachers for Global Classrooms Program.

The Program is a year-long professional development opportunity for U.S. elementary, middle, and high school teachers to develop skills for preparing students for a competitive global economy. The program equips teachers to bring an international perspective to their schools through targeted training, experience abroad, and global collaboration. The 901 is proud of you and can't wait to have you share all that you learn with the BV community !

Buckeye Valley West was recently recognized as the top fundraising school by the Leukemia & Lymphoma Society Central Ohio Chapter for their participation in the 2019-2020 Pennies for Patients Campaign. BV West raised $9,089.76 to claim the top spot. Students and staff raised funds throughout the year during spirit week, by hosting a Kona day, and by creating a kindness photo opportunity. The teachers incorporated the campaign in their project based learning activities by having students sort, count, record, and total money in each classroom.

In addition, BV West was recognized as a Loyal Lincoln Award recipient for their five years of participation in the Pennies for Patients Campaign. Congratulations on a job well done Barons - the 901 is proud of your continued commitment to serving others!

post_text:
Leadership Opportunity for High School Juniors and Seniors to serve on Teen Ambassador Board in Ohio Attorney General's office

Ohio Attorney General Dave Yost announced that his office is now accepting applications for its Teen Ambassador Board. The Attorney General’s Teen Ambassador Board consists of high school juniors and seniors from public, private, charter and online schools in Ohio. The mission of the program is to provide Ohio’s future leaders with an inside look at Ohio law and government.

Board members advise the office on issues relating to teens and work with their peers to develop solutions to those issues. They serve a one-year term during which they convene twice in Columbus and participate in activities across the state.

Ohio high school students who will be juniors or seniors during the 2020-21 academic year are eligible to apply for the Teen Ambassador Board.

Applications are due June 26, 2020. The application can be found on the Ohio Attorney General’s website. https://buff.ly/2NrVp8N

shared_text:
Delaware Area Career Center
June 17 at 10:19 AM ·

Tina Francis, DACC-Buckeye Valley Middle School CBI teacher, has been awarded the 2020 Dr. G. James Pinchak Service Learning Award. Dr. G. James Pinchak was a friend to CBI and one of the most knowledgeable and caring partners for career technical education.

Ms. Francis was recognized for her work with Pennies for Patients at BVMS and has been coordinating this fundraiser with her students for the Leukemia & Lymphoma Society for the past ten years. During that time they have raised over $33,000 for pediatric cancer research. Congratulations Tina Francis!

post_text: Another BV senior (correction GRADUATE) making headlines!
shared_text:
Delaware County Fair, Delaware Ohio
May 18 at 12:00 AM ·

Bryce Alkire is a 2020 graduate from Buckeye Valley High School. He played varsity soccer and was involved in marching and concert band during his 4 years at Buckeye Valley. Bryce has been involved in 4-H for 12 years and in that time has served as his club’s president and vice president. Through 4-H, he has shown pet rabbits, breeding rabbits, and market hogs. In the fall Bryce will continue his education at Columbus State pursuing a degree in forensic science and Spanish. Best of luck and congratulations, Bryce!

post_text: Well done BV Lacrosse! PROUD of your support for the community during this unprecedented time!
shared_text:
Common Ground Free Store Ministries
May 13 at 3:52 PM ·

Ready for some good news today? Jack Scheeler, a senior at Buckeye Valley High School and a member of the Men’s Lacrosse team, presented our Executive Director with a donation check today. The team wasn’t able to complete their season and many of the parents were kind enough to choose to donate the collected team meal money instead of having it refunded. What a generous group! We are grateful for our wonderful community! 💙

These ladies have been with the program since the beginning and are leaving a legacy for years to come. Thank you Class of 2020 and congratulations to all of the athletes who have worn the Brown and Gold!

March 20 at 4:10 PM ·

𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐁𝐕 "𝐂𝐨𝐦𝐦𝐮𝐧𝐢𝐭𝐲" 𝐬𝐩𝐢𝐫𝐢𝐭 𝐰𝐞𝐚𝐫 𝐢𝐬 𝐫𝐞𝐚𝐝𝐲. 𝐖𝐞 𝐰𝐨𝐫𝐤𝐞𝐝 𝐪𝐮𝐢𝐜𝐤𝐥𝐲 𝐭𝐨 𝐠𝐚𝐢𝐧 𝐝𝐢𝐬𝐭𝐫𝐢𝐜𝐭 𝐚𝐩𝐩𝐫𝐨𝐯𝐚𝐥, 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐭𝐡𝐞𝐬𝐞 𝐚𝐫𝐞 𝐠𝐨𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐭𝐨 𝐛𝐞 𝐬𝐨𝐥𝐝 𝐃𝐈𝐒𝐓𝐑𝐈𝐂𝐓 𝐰𝐢𝐝𝐞 𝐰𝐢𝐭𝐡 𝐩𝐫𝐨𝐜𝐞𝐞𝐝𝐬 𝐠𝐨𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐭𝐨 𝐚𝐥𝐥 𝐟𝐨𝐮𝐫 𝐬𝐜𝐡𝐨𝐨𝐥𝐬!

We understand that not everyone is in the position to purchase, so do not feel obligated. We're all in this together, and just wanted to show solidarity.

Many thanks to Chrissy Payne and Sophie Stump for helping with the design and approval. And again, thanks to Derrick Laura Begue Cobb for the saying.

We hope you love it. The shirts it is on are the really soft vintage t-shirts and the sweatshirt is the same super soft sweatshirt as last year, just without darker arms.

You can order items here until March 29th: https://www.marktapparel.com/store/c44/Buckeye_Valley_Schools.html

post_text:
The District has some additional information regarding the emergency food relief efforts:

Buckeye Valley will be providing meals for those students who have applied and qualified for the State of Ohio’s free and reduced lunch price program at no charge to these families. Beginning Tuesday March 17, Buckeye Valley will offer drive through services at Buckeye Valley Middle School, Buckeye Valley East Elementary, and Buckeye Valley West Elementary Buildings during the hours of 4pm - 6pm. Families can visit these locations to pick up lunch and breakfast items for their students.

And now for some details:
* Starting Tuesday, March 17th, parents can pick up 4 days worth of meals from 4 pm - 6pm.
* On Wednesday, March 18th, parents who weren't able to make it Tuesday, can pick up 3 days worth of meals from 4pm - pm .
* On Monday, March 23rd, parents can pick up 5 days worth of meals from 4pm - 6pm.
* Please note: The District will not provide meals during the regularly scheduled Spring Break (March 30 - April 3).

post_text:
This week the BVMS Builder's Club supported the Send a Smile Today project by making 200 handmade cards that will be sent to cancer patients throughout the US to provide hope, love and support to those patients undergoing treatment.

The Builders Club provides middle school students the opportunity to work together in service to school and community and develop leadership skills while fostering the development of strong moral character and encouraging loyalty to school, community and nation.

Students meet monthly to plan and execute service projects throughout the school year. For more information on the Send A Smile Today program visit: https://sendasmiletoday.org/

post_text:
The 2019 Buckeye Valley Hall of Fame Class Inductees:

SUZETTE HALL:
Suzette Hall became involved in the Buckeye Valley district when her family moved to the community. She has been an active member of the BV community for the past three decades. She served as a member of the Radnor Elementary PTO, she worked on numerous school levy campaigns, served as a member of both the music and athletic boosters.

Suzette has three grown children all of whom are BVHS alumni and three grandchildren currently enrolled in the BV district.

TIM HARREL
Tim Harrel graduated from Buckeye Valley 1976. Over the years, Tim has coached baseball and basketball for the Buckeye Valley youth. He began his involvement with BV Athletics with his son and to coach today

For years, Tim worked the midnight shift at the BV fair booth - cooking and getting ready for the breakfast shifts. Tim served as the Joint Booster Treasurer from 1997 to 2001.

Tim and his wife, Marjorie celebrated 41 years of marriage this year and through all his coaching and volunteering she has been there by his side.

post_text: Thank you Scowden Family for the update - the entire BV community is fighting with you!
shared_text:
April Lowry Scowden
December 8, 2019 at 9:25 AM ·

Troy had a great night! If his only complaint is a headache and a bigger bed I’m happy. He answered all of the doctors questions and commands throughout the night. He’s still complaining of his right shoulder hurting but X-ray shows it’s not broke. He’s still in ICU but improving every day. They are talking about starting him on a liquid diet, he’s not thrilled, as he really wants a Burger King whopper and to be back on the court. As a mom and all the fans at the game, watching this unfold was not easy. Jeremy and I are thrilled with where he’s at already. I want all the students to know he’s going to be ok. While a fractured skull with a brain bleed is serious, things could have been much worse. The doctors and nurses have been great and are also happy with where he is. You expect to see a sprained ankle or knee at a basketball game not this. We truly feel like the power of prayer has helped all of us through this. Thanks for all the texts, calls, etc. Go Barons! ❤️

This is information from Varsity Head Basketball Coach Andy Gast who has been in contact with the family of sophomore, Troy Scowden, who was injured during the Varsity Basketball Game last night:

Troy suffered a skull fracture as a result of a fall during the game. His team of doctors at Nationwide Children's Hospital is evaluating his condition to determine if surgery is necessary. At this time, no visitors are permitted but the family asks for continued thoughts and prayers.

The Scowden Family will continue to stay in touch with Coach Gast and will share updates on Troys condition as the weekend progresses.

post_text: What a great program. Thank you Delaware Area Career Center for making it happen!
shared_text:
Delaware Area Career Center
October 4, 2019 at 3:23 PM ·

October 4th is Manufacturing Day & we partnered with businesses right here in Delaware County to learn more about all of the career paths & options available to students after high school. Across the board, we heard that today's manufacturing requires creativity, teamwork, reliability, & a good attitude. For those willing to learn on-the-job and work their way up through the company, there are many great careers to be had.

8th grade CBI students from Delaware City Schools & Buckeye Valley Local School District toured RedBuilt, Charter NEX Films, Columbus Advanced Manufacturing Systems, Inc., Federal Heath Sign Company LLC, & V&P Hydraulic Products, LLC Thank you to our wonderful hosts & to City of Delaware, Ohio - Government for introducing us to a few new companies this year.

8th grade CBI students from Delaware City Schools & Buckeye Valley Local School District toured RedBuilt, Charter NEX Films, Columbus Advanced Manufacturing Systems, Inc., Federal Heath Sign Company LLC, & V&P Hydraulic Products, LLC Thank you to our wonderful hosts & to City of Delaware, Ohio - Government for introducing us to a few new companies this year.

post_text:
Today, as the staff of Buckeye Valley Schools gathered for a day of professional development, Superintendent Miller launched a year-long Campaign entitled NeverStop.

This campaign is challenging our staff to acknowledge those things that they are doing everyday to better our students, each other and the community in which we live. But it does not stop with the BV staff. We know our students are doing amazing things every single day - in the classrooms, on the field, on the stage and in their communities. We want to not only recognize these things but celebrate them and most importantly we want to encourage everyone to NeverStop doing things that make us as individuals and a district better.

We hope you will follow this campaign as we weave it throughout the district classrooms, on district social media platforms (#NeverStop), in district publications and in our everyday lives. Today Superintendent Miller encouraged district staff to NeverStop Teaching and making a difference in the lives of their students.

post_text:
Today the Ohio Department of Education released its annual report cards for all schools in the state.

The Buckeye Valley District was awarded a "B". Superintendent Miller indicated that he was proud of the Buckeye Valley students and staff and pleased with the overall grade, noting specifically the strong Progress/ Value Added measure and pointing out that BV students continue to exceed the growth targets established by the Ohio Department of Education . "While the district continues to trend in a positive direction, there are areas that the district needs to improve upon",stated Mr. Miller, indicating that building and district leadership will be reviewing the report card data thoroughly in the upcoming weeks to build upon strengths as well address any deficiencies.
